Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 39th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
We got exploding rockets, a case for AgARDA & a case against safetyism, and=
 longevity learnings. At bit all over the place, but in a good way.
If you like it, subscribe! We=E2=80=99re tantalizingly close to 200k:
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by... Axios Pro [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/0ed47b3b-d41c-4c94-a11e-f5c28d92be34?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Listen, it's tough at there right now: layoffs, multiple compression, inter=
est rate uncertainty, and even sudden banking crises =E2=80=94 there's a lo=
t going on and the Axios Pro [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ed47b3b-d41c-=
4c94-a11e-f5c28d92be34?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] newsroom is here to provide clarity. Axios' industry-leadi=
ng journalists =E2=80=94 like Dan Primack=C2=A0=E2=80=94 help contextualize=
 how this downturn is impacting dealmaking in your industry.
Why it matters: Optimism doesn=E2=80=99t mean putting your head in the sand=
=2E Get data.=C2=A0Not Boring readers=
 can=C2=A0download Axios=C2=A0Pro's late=
st industry report [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ed47b3b-d41c-4c94-a11e-=
f5c28d92be34?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ]=C2=A0for free to learn=C2=A0what the current economic cooldown means=
 for your bottom line, and how to plan for a possible recession.
Go deeper:=C2=A0The Axios Pro [ https://substack.com/redirect/0ed47b3b-d41c=
-4c94-a11e-f5c28d92be34?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] newsroom delivers aggregated data and analysis from the b=
iggest players in VC, PE and M&A, plus key industry trends and takeaways to=
 inform every critical decision you=E2=80=99ll make this year.=C2=A0 If you=
r work touches fintech, health tech, climate, media or retail (which if you=
're reading this, it likely does) this might be the most important report y=
ou read all year.=C2=A0
(1) Starship Flight Test
On 4/20 (of course, nice), SpaceX achieved its primary objective of getting=
 Starship off the ground.=20
Starship, which will eventually attempt to take humans to the moon and Mars=
, is the largest and most powerful rocket ever constructed, and is now the =
largest and most powerful rocket ever to launch. Even though the rocket exp=
loded minutes after launch, it was a big accomplishment to just get this bi=
gboi in the air.=20
We=E2=80=99ve been critical of Elon=E2=80=99s work at Twitter. It=E2=80=99s=
 easy to forget that he=E2=80=99s working on civilization-changing, big eng=
ineering problems like Starship when he=E2=80=99s being a poopoohead on his=
 rotting website. But props where props are due. Duality of man and all tha=
t.=20
While Elon=E2=80=99s biggest critics and those who generally dislike cool s=
hit are focusing on the fact that the rocket blew up, launching and learnin=
g on a budget that=E2=80=99s minuscule compared to NASA=E2=80=99s [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/3bcfc40a-7797-4d91-b0d7-d1c3ec986cbf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is a big accomplishme=
nt. SpaceX continues to make the world stop and stare in wonder, and we nee=
d more of that.
(2) How did solar power get cheap? Part I [ https://substack.com/redirect/1=
495f388-ea93-47b1-a534-8c47d1e42d10?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] & Part II [ https://substack.com/redirect/def=
c09e4-a974-41d0-809b-593810083951?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Brian Potter [ https://substack.com/redirect/4b3c9918-4aa9-46e7-8249-3804c3=
ced856?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 in Construction Pysics
Solar PV=E2=80=99s low cost is the result of it steadily falling in price o=
ver many decades. In 1957 solar PV electricity cost roughly $300,000 per me=
gawatt-hour in 2019 dollars. By 2019, in the sunniest locations that had fa=
llen to roughly $20 per megawatt-hour, 15,000 times less. And it's still ge=
tting cheaper.
We love us a good learning curve here at Not Boring. From Moore=E2=80=99s L=
aw to DNA sequencing to solar PV prices, these curves show costs declining =
and performance improving exponentially over time, as if by magic =F0=9F=AA=
=84
But the most magical thing about learning curves is that they=E2=80=99re no=
t magical at all. They=E2=80=99re the result of millions of individual, cor=
porate, and national efforts over decades that somehow shake out into these=
 relatively smooth, beautiful curves.=20
In this two-part piece, Brian Potter, the author of one of our favorite blo=
gs, Construction Physics, which breaks down why things are built the way th=
ey are, explains everything that=E2=80=99s gone into shrinking the cost of =
solar PV electricity by 15,000x over the past seven decades.=20
From the earliest exploration of the photovoltaic effect in 1839 by the dad=
 of the guy who discovered radioactivity to the invention of the modern PV =
cell at (where else?) Bell Labs in 1954 to the first big solar PV purchases=
 by (who else?) US and Russian aerospace and defense agencies in 1958 to th=
e international competition across the US, Japan, Germany, and China to pro=
duce the most and cheapest cells, Potter=E2=80=99s piece is a comprehensive=
 look at how one of the world=E2=80=99s most important curves came to be.=
=20
We celebrate humanity=E2=80=99s big, flashy achievements here, but sometime=
s, it=E2=80=99s the composition of small improvements that power the greate=
st progress. =20
(3) The Case for AgARDA [ https://substack.com/redirect/d961416a-9997-4340-=
8676-ee4d7bc92426?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]
Adin Richards for The Institute for Progress
ARPA programs succeed [ https://substack.com/redirect/801011f0-ae07-44b6-88=
d7-59be8da610f7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] because of intense focus on a few important objectives, pursued n=
imbly with whatever technology is best suited to meet the goal. AgARDA shou=
ld focus on three primary technological areas:=C2=A0
Passive monitoring of crop fields and livestock for known and novel disease=
s
Genetically engineering more productive, stress-tolerant plants that are le=
ss reliant on farming inputs
New ways of producing calories =E2=80=94 such as precision fermentation [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/6f9d00c6-253a-463e-a20e-b5a697225d8d?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] or microbes tha=
t process waste [ https://substack.com/redirect/c40221dd-4a91-4350-9baa-79b=
9ead85ad8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] =E2=80=94 that are less susceptible to climate and disease threats than=
 field crops and livestock
The U.S. was once the leader in farming innovation, but that position has w=
eakened over time as we=E2=80=99ve transformed into a services economy. Ric=
hards makes the case that the government needs to fund and support the new =
Agricultural Advanced Research Development Agency (AgARDA) it created in th=
e 2018 Farm Bill and details the top three initiatives the agency should fo=
cus on. Ultimately, it comes down to protecting a U.S. leadership position =
in food and monitoring threats against our food supply.
The ARPA/ARDA (Advanced Research Project/Development Agencies) model is fas=
cinating and effective. You likely know DARPA (Defense Advance Research Pro=
jects Agency), which was deeply involved in the development of the Internet=
, GPS, and drones. Because of DARPA=E2=80=99s effectiveness in funding moon=
shot tech and shepherding it to market via DOD contracts, the government ha=
s begun experimenting with more ARPA/ARDAs recently, like ARPA-E (2009) for=
 energy and ARPA-H (2022) for biotech and health. While results have been m=
ixed, these programs have the potential to combine the resources of the gov=
ernment with the flexibility of venture-like funding models.=20
As with solar and so many of our biggest technological achievements, we can=
 tackle bigger challenges when government, academia, and industry work toge=
ther effectively, and we hope AgARDA can have a DARPA-like impact on food.=
=20
(4) Against Safetyism [ https://substack.com/redirect/b554c3d5-e2d9-4d19-99=
c5-cc010857bd52?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]
Byrne Hobart and Tobias Huber for Pirate Wires
Now, whether we think that an AI apocalypse is imminent or the lab-leak hyp=
othesis is correct or not, by mitigating or suppressing visible risks, safe=
tyism is often creating invisible or hidden risks that are far more consequ=
ential or impactful than the risks it attempts to mitigate. In a way, this =
makes sense: creating a new technology and deploying it widely entails a de=
finite vision for the future. But a focus on the risks means a definite vis=
ion of the past, and a more stochastic model of what the future might hold.=
 Given time=E2=80=99s annoying habit of only moving in one direction, we ha=
ve no choice but to live in somebody=E2=80=99s future =E2=80=94 the questio=
n is whether it=E2=80=99s somebody with a plan or somebody with a neurosis.
Call it safetyism. Risk aversion. Doomerism. Call it whatever you want. (We=
=E2=80=99ll call it safetyism for consistency=E2=80=99s sake). But freaking=
 out about the future, and letting that freakout prevent advancement has be=
come an increasingly popular stance. Pessimists sound smart, optimists make=
 money. Safetyists sound smart, optimists make progress.=20
Friend of the newsletter, Byrne Hobart, and Tobias Huber explain why safety=
ism is both illogical and dangerous. These two quotes capture the crux of t=
he argument:
Obsessively attempting to eliminate all visible risks often creates invisib=
le risks that are far more consequential for human flourishing.
Whether it=E2=80=99s nuclear energy, AI, biotech, or any other emerging tec=
hnology, what all these cases have in common is that =E2=80=94 by obstructi=
ng technological progress =E2=80=94 safetyism has an extremely high civiliz=
ational opportunity cost.
We worry about the potential risks of nuclear energy, we get the reality of=
 dirtier and more deadly fossil fuels. Often, the downsides created by safe=
tyism aren=E2=80=99t as clear as the nuclear example: =E2=80=9Cby mitigatin=
g or suppressing visible risks, safetyism is often creating invisible or hi=
dden risks that are far more consequential or impactful than the risks it a=
ttempts to mitigate.=E2=80=9D While we worry about AI killing us all, for e=
xample, millions will die of diseases that AI could help detect or even cur=
e.=20
This isn=E2=80=99t a call to scream YOLO as we indiscriminately create new =
technologies with zero regards for the consequences, but it=E2=80=99s an im=
portant reminder that trying to play it safe is often the riskiest move of =
all.=20
(5) Peter Attia - The Portfolio to Live Longer [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/e478dfb6-d844-4b4b-b1da-b28a85258e01?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Longevity and optimism are intertwined. Longevity folks want to live longer=
 because they believe life is worth living for as long and as well as you c=
an. Your average optimist probably has a pretty similar perspective, even i=
f they are not singularly focused on the length and quality of life. To car=
e about living well is to be an optimist.
So if you=E2=80=99re reading this newsletter, you=E2=80=99re likely interes=
ted in longevity (or healthspan) =E2=80=94 and Dr. Peter Attia is the world=
=E2=80=99s leading (or most popular) expert on the topic. He recently relea=
sed his long-awaited book =E2=80=9COutlive: The Science and Art of Longevit=
y [ https://substack.com/redirect/0c47b9dd-748f-464b-b19f-e04b28218c48?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D a=
nd went on Patrick O=E2=80=99Shaughness=E2=80=99y podcast to discuss it at =
length (see what I did there?).
According to Attia, there are five areas over which we have agency that can=
 meaningful impact healthspan: nutrition, exercise, sleep, pharmacology (dr=
ugs, supplements, etc), and tools around mental health. But these are not a=
ll created equal: exercise has a disproportionate impact on longevity and h=
ealthspan.
Speaking of exercise and supplements=E2=80=A6
Bonus: Dan on The Danny Miranda Podcast: The Creatine King [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/bea86c88-a41c-4a06-9d6f-056c0d4745e7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=20
Packy here, sneaking this in while Dan=E2=80=99s not looking. Dan did his b=
iggest podcast interview yet, talking about creating Create [ https://subst=
